Here, n is the total number of points extracted from the considered spatial entity, and xi, yi, and zi are the coordinates of the points extracted from it, respectively. For the visualization of the geometric center see Figure 2.2 (a). In oder to focus on the topologic arrangement of chromosome territories and to neglect the effects coming from differences in their shape, the geometric centers of these spatial entities are used instead of their surface points. This leads to notably different results as the shape of replication loci or genes, and especially of homologue CTs can significantly vary in different nuclei even when the relative positions of their geometric centers are identical. All calculations presented in this thesis are based on the geometric center of spatial entities, therefore, the mathematical analysis involved ignores the spatial extensions of the considered objects. However, the shape of replication loci or genes, and especially of

25

2. Methods

homologue CTs can significantly vary in different nuclei even when the relative positions of their geometric centers are identical. When the number of geometric centers describing the arrangement is too small, this can lead to a confusion of the quantitative measure (see section 5.1).

